75–1438","from 1432 to 1439":"from 1432 to 1439","27 Jan 1459 ":"27 January 1459","March 1436":"March 1436","1370":"1370","about 1419":"about 1419","1459":"1459","1436":"1436","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1398":"1398","about 1436":"about 1436","30 July 1438":"30 July 1438","1375":"1375","about 1398":"about 1398","about 1397":"about 1397","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Clapham, Sussex, England":"Clapham, Sussex, England","Echingham, Sussex, England (United Kingdom)":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Clapham, West Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni":"Clapham, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Michelgrove, Sussex, England":"Michelgrove, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"alias","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Luis, Juan, Manuel, Jorge, Jesus, Arturo, Ramon, Pedro, Francisco, Miguel.","Spanish: from the medieval personal name <i>Arias</i>, of disputed origin.","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Spanish surname (see above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Faulconer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Faulkner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Faulkner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fauconer</i>, <i>fauk(e)ner</i>, <i>falconer</i> ‘falconer’ (Old French <i>fau(l)connier</i>), an occupational name for someone who kept and trained falcons (a common feudal service). Falconry was a tremendously popular sport among the aristocracy in medieval Europe, and most great houses had their falconers. The surname could also have arisen as a metonymic occupational name for someone who operated the siege gun known as a <i>falcon</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":57,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Michelgrove alias Faulconer was born about 1398, in Clapham, Sussex, England, his father, John Fauconer alias Michelgrove, was 29 and his mother, Joan Whegleton, was 25. He married Joan Shoyswell about 1419, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He lived in Michelgrove, Sussex, England in 1435. He died on 27 January 1459, in Clapham, Sussex, England, at the age of 62, and was buried in Clapham, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1398–27 Jan 1459 ":"umbes 1398–27. jaanuar 1459","1398–1459":"1398–1459","1400–1459":"1400–1459","1420–1464":"1420–1464","1436–1459":"1436–1459","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1375–1438":"1375–1438","from 1432 to 1439":"1432 kuni 1439","27 Jan 1459 ":"27. jaanuar 1459","March 1436":"märts 1436","1370":"1370","about 1419":"umbes 1419","1459":"1459","1436":"1436","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","1398":"1398","about 1436":"umbes 1436","30 July 1438":"30. juuli 1438","1375":"1375","about 1398":"umbes 1398","about 1397":"umbes 1397","1439":"